In 2025, the Czech automotive giant Škoda Auto produced over 1,043,900 vehicles @skoda_stats. At the time of writing, the company is actively manufacturing and selling around 11 different models, including the popular Škoda Octavia, Škoda Fabia, and Škoda Superb. It is pretty reasonable to say that there is a lot of work being done on the research and development side to keep up with demand for new cars and to keep improving existing models. 

The process of designing and manufacturing a car is highly iterative. Theory alone can get you relatively far, but at the end of the day, even in a strictly controlled environment, many factors can affect the car's performance, and the only way to really understand how it performs is to test it in real life. Testing is conducted by taking the car on a standardized test drive on a public road, a test track, or in a wind tunnel. #footnote[Processes described are specific to the Thermosystem department of Škoda Auto, but the general principles are likely to be similar across the whole company]. Depending on the test, specific parameters of the drive are standardized, such as speed, drive duration, and, in the case of a wind tunnel, air pressure, temperature, humidity, and the track's incline.

During the drive, a wide array of sensors collects data on various aspects of the car's performance, generating a large amount of telemetry. Tests may be conducted multiple times a day. After a while, the amount of collected data becomes quite large, making it difficult to analyze it all manually. This is where the need for a software solution arises.

The first step in the process will be to analyze the engineers' and technicians' current workflow for data analysis and identify pain points in their process. This will involve conducting interviews and observations to understand how they currently analyze the data, which tools they use, and the challenges they face. Based on this analysis, we will search for existing software solutions that could address these pain points and evaluate their suitability for our specific use case. If we find a suitable solution, we will then customize it to fit our needs.

If no suitable solution is found, requirements for a new software solution will be drawn up, including all the specific features and functionalities users might need for an efficient workflow. An important part of this process will also be to define the software's technical stack and architecture, ensuring it is scalable and maintainable for future developers.